{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1c991ced-0ddf-4fea-a422-ccea335a3c76","content":"This is a **TUnit** project (v0.6.120), which uses **Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP)** — not VSTest. To filter by class, use `--treenode-filter`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter pattern is `/<Assembly>/<Namespace>/<Class>/<Test>`, and `*` acts as a wildcard. This matches both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds` from the `SmsNotificationTests` class.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6b182c3f-ef26-4dca-9e8b-a14246caa031","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) by default, not VSTest. For MTP-based TUnit projects, you filter by class using the `--treenode-filter` option.\n\nThe command would be:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nOr with `dotnet test`:\n\nTUnit 0.6.x uses MTP. With `dotnet test` and MTP, filtering works differently. Let me think...\n\nFor TUnit with MTP, the correct way is:\n\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nor with `dotnet test`:\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nBoth approaches use the treenode filter pattern to target the specific test class.","outputTokens":532},"id":"164ae8dc-ea93-457e-b5ad-56e8a453e523","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:34:56.398Z","parentId":"82a058bd-9b03-49b3-bdc9-6f9c7ab0bfcd"}
